					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/litfried" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391439); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1391439&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225575" alt="Litfried" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1391439)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/litfried" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391439); return false;" >Litfried</a></span> <span class="odate time_1393502729 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Feb 2014 12:05</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1979376">
									

<p>I'd agree with TL333s here about the dialogue. It is really quite poor in a number of places: excessive use of full stops to indicate long pauses where an adjectival description would be better (e.g. &quot;Uh, so?&quot; said Jack slowly.), lots of clumsy verbal stalls, bad punctuation (missing commas being the worst offender), and quite flippant word usage. I'd recommend a re-write of the dialogue, as it would seriously improve the tone of the piece.</p>
<p>That said, I liked everything else. I like Directorate K, I like the characters (though the protagonist could stand to be a little less dumbfounded all the time, I heartily approve of his first impression being that his boss has flipped and needs help), and I love Rube-Goldberg chains of events.</p>
<p>Overall, a solid +1, but if I were you, I would work on dialogue.</p>

							</div>

								
					
