								<div class="title" id="post-title-1983969">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/abettik" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1700758); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1700758&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225575" alt="Abettik" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1700758)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/abettik" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1700758); return false;" >Abettik</a></span> <span class="odate time_1393987384 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Mar 2014 02:43</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1983969">
									

<p>Thanks for the critique, and also the praise.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I appreciate your thoughts on dialogue, and would definitely be open to hearing more opinions on different dialogue styles and choices.</p>
<p>However, I carefully and deliberately wrote the dialogue in such a way as to have the punctuation and word choice match the flow of an actual conversation, and to subtly point out the mood of the speaker. Whether it was effective or not, I suppose, depends on the reader.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Absolutely,&quot; he replied. &quot;I sure will. May I return to my desk.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Even though it's technically a question, Jack is speaking so flatly that it doesn't sound like a question so much as a statement. I chose to illustrate this by using a period, rather than saying, &quot;Jack said flatly&quot; which I personally feel isn't as effective.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;What.&quot; Jack thought he misheard. He realized he didn't. &quot;The. Fuck.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I could say, &quot;'What the fuck,' Jack said slowly,&quot; or even, &quot;Whaaaaaaaaaat theeeeeeee fuuuuuuuuuck???&quot; but these all have a different feel from &quot;What. The. Fuck.&quot; which I personally feel shows his confusion and disbelief more than the others. It shows his mind is working as he tries to sputter out words. Of course, I could say, &quot;he stammered, his mind reeling as he uselessly sputtered out words.&quot; but that's lengthy and breaks flow in my opinion.</p>
<p>Just my thoughts. Dialogue doesn't need perfect punctuation because we rarely speak in perfect punctuation. I wouldn't mind a full thread on this somewhere.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
