				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/litfried" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391439); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1391439&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225575" alt="Litfried" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1391439)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/litfried" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391439); return false;" >Litfried</a></span> <span class="odate time_1394010529 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Mar 2014 09:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1984221">
									

<p>You make an interesting point at the end there - it's certainly the case that we don't speak with perfect punctuation, and so many media (by which I mean written fiction, films, TV, etc&#8230;) end up with unnatural-sounding dialogue because of tradition that it actually becomes strange when more realistic speech is written (see, for example, <em>The Big Lebowski</em>) - although I personally think that realistic talking is always the best when possible.</p>
<p>I myself prefer to have totally correct punctuation within speech and use language to reflect the cadence and rhythm, but I can see how using punctuation to achieve the same effect is equally valid. To me as a reader, it breaks the flow and immersion a bit, but I realise this is just my interpretation, and that to others it could be easier.</p>
<p>Bottom line is it's the writer's choice, and as long as it isn't a deal breaker for the majority of the audience then the writer can be said to have made the correct choice. For me, your stylistic decisions certainly weren't enough to prevent my upvote. And I thank you for taking the time to explain your thought process to me.</p>

							</div>

								
					
